          "body": "Where Mark records the centurion saying *truly this man was the Son of God* (Mark 15:39), Luke records *certainly this man was *dikaios** (23:47). The variation is not contradiction; it is Lukan emphasis. *Dikaios* (righteous, innocent) is the climactic term in a chapter that has used the cognate *aitios* three times (23:4, 14, 22). The Gentile executioner — the very man who supervised the crucifixion — pronounces the verdict that the Jewish court refused: this man was righteous. Isaiah 53:11 stands behind the word: *the Righteous One, My Servant, will justify the many*. Luke is showing that the cross does not merely fail human justice; it succeeds in divine justice, and even Gentile eyes can see it. The centurion's glorification of God (23:47) is the first Gentile worship at the cross, anticipating Acts."
